    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-07-31T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-07-31T00:00:00-05:00" n="241"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d241">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Roosevelt Papers: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Prime Minister <persName type="from">Churchill</persName> to
                        President <persName type="to">Roosevelt</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d241fn1">Sent to Washington by the United States Military
                        Attaché, London, via Army channels; forwarded by the White House Map Room to
                        Roosevelt, who was then at Hyde Park, as telegram No. <gloss
                            target="#t_White1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">White</hi>
                        </gloss> 6. Concerning Roosevelt’s movements from July 30 to August 9, 1943,
                        see <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_406">p. 406</ref>, fn.
                        1.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">most secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-07-31">31st July
                            1943</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>No. 394. <gloss target="#t_FNP1">Former Naval Person</gloss> to President
                    personal and most secret. Your 334.<note n="2" xml:id="d241fn2">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_521">p. 521</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>My position is that once Mussolini and the Fascists are gone, I will deal with
                    any Italian authority who can deliver the goods. I am not in the least afraid
                    for this purpose of seeming to recognize the House of Savoy or Badoglio,
                    provided they are the ones who can make the Italians do what we need for our war
                    purposes. Those purposes would certainly be hindered by chaos, bolshevisation or
                    civil war. We have no right to lay undue burdens on our troops. It may well be
                    that after the armistice terms have been accepted, both the King and Badoglio
                    will sink under the odium of surrender and that the Crown Prince and a new Prime
                    Minister may be chosen.</p>
                <p>I should deprecate any pronouncement about self determination at the present
                    time, beyond what is implicit in the Atlantic charter.<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d241fn3">Released by Roosevelt and Churchill, August 14, 1941. For
                        text see Department of State, Executive Agreement Series No. 236; 55 <gloss
                            target="#t_Stat1">Stat</gloss>. (2) 1603; <ref
                            target="frus1941v01#pg_368">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1941, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, pp. 368</ref>–<ref
                            target="frus1941v01#pg_369">369</ref>.</note> I agree with you that we
                    must be very careful not to throw everything into the melting pot.</p>
            </div>
